TY  - JOUR
T1  - Behavior in a Dynamic Decision Problem: An Analysis of Experimental Evidence Using a Bayesian Type Classification Algorithm
AU  - Houser, Daniel
AU  - Keane, Michael
AU  - McCabe, Kevin
Y1  - 2004/05/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0262.2004.00512.x
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 781
EP  - 822
VL  - 72
IS  - 3
KW  - Dynamic programming
KW  - Gibbs sampling
KW  - Bayesian decision theory
KW  - experimental economics
KW  - behavioral economics
KW  - heuristics
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0262.2004.00512.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Different people may use different strategies, or decision rules, when solving complex decision problems. We provide a new Bayesian procedure for drawing inferences about the nature and number of decision rules present in a population, and use it to analyze the behaviors of laboratory subjects confronted with a difficult dynamic stochastic decision problem. Subjects practiced before playing for money. Based on money round decisions, our procedure classifies subjects into three types, which we label ?Near Rational,??Fatalist,? and ?Confused.? There is clear evidence of continuity in subjects' behaviors between the practice and money rounds: types who performed best in practice also tended to perform best when playing for money. However, the agreement between practice and money play is far from perfect. The divergences appear to be well explained by a combination of type switching (due to learning and/or increased effort in money play) and errors in our probabilistic type assignments.
ER  - 

