TY  - JOUR
T1  - Repeated Games with Private Monitoring: Two Players
AU  - Matsushima, Hitoshi
Y1  - 2004/05/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0262.2004.00513.x
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 823
EP  - 852
VL  - 72
IS  - 3
KW  - Discounted repeated games
KW  - private monitoring
KW  - review strategies
KW  - folk theorem
KW  - macro shock
KW  - efficiency
KW  - price-setting duopoly
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0262.2004.00513.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We investigate two-player infinitely repeated games where the discount factor is less than but close to unity. Monitoring is private and players cannot communicate. We require no condition concerning the accuracy of players' monitoring technology. We show the folk theorem for the prisoners' dilemma with conditional independence. We also investigate more general games where players' private signals are correlated only through an unobservable macro shock. We show that efficiency is sustainable for generic private signal structures when the size of the set of private signals is sufficiently large. Finally, we show that cartel collusion is sustainable in price-setting duopoly.
ER  - 

